00:02:08.174 --> 00:02:09.882
AUDIENCE: The Earth's
gravitational field

00:02:09.882 --> 00:02:12.082
is [INAUDIBLE] so
it all evaporates.

00:02:12.082 --> 00:02:13.040
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Yeah.

00:02:13.040 --> 00:02:13.880
Well, not all of it.

00:02:13.880 --> 00:02:15.480
There's still some of it.

00:02:15.480 --> 00:02:18.170
There's some of it with
which we make from.

00:02:18.170 --> 00:02:20.880
But where is it?

00:02:20.880 --> 00:02:22.320
It's tied up.

00:02:22.320 --> 00:02:23.920
It's busy.

00:02:23.920 --> 00:02:24.490
You know?

00:02:24.490 --> 00:02:27.340
And you got to say,
hey, I need you.

00:02:27.340 --> 00:02:29.410
Get off of that methane
molecule or get off

00:02:29.410 --> 00:02:32.830
of this other molecule
and come over here and be

00:02:32.830 --> 00:02:34.510
an energy carrier for me.

00:02:34.510 --> 00:02:40.360
That takes energy to make the
hydrogen be available to use

00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:43.300
as an energy carrier.

00:02:43.300 --> 00:02:45.854
And then the other
problem is what?

00:02:45.854 --> 00:02:46.730
AUDIENCE: Storing it.

00:02:46.730 --> 00:02:47.938
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Storing it.

00:02:47.938 --> 00:02:48.582
Right.

00:02:48.582 --> 00:02:49.540
Because it's very hard.

00:02:49.540 --> 00:02:52.970
So I'm going to talk
about the second problem

00:02:52.970 --> 00:02:57.920
because, again, there's sort
of a molecular solution that's

00:02:57.920 --> 00:03:00.080
really exciting where
computation can play a role.

00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:00.580
OK.

00:03:00.580 --> 00:03:02.662
So I'm just going to
spend the first 15,

00:03:02.662 --> 00:03:04.120
20 minutes here
talking about this.

00:03:04.120 --> 00:03:07.505
I think this is--

00:03:07.505 --> 00:03:11.070
there are high opinions
about hydrogen-- gesundheit--

00:03:11.070 --> 00:03:12.150
storage.

00:03:12.150 --> 00:03:14.280
And the hydrogen economy--

00:03:14.280 --> 00:03:16.650
the hydrogen economy
is this sort of vision

00:03:16.650 --> 00:03:20.100
that President Bush put forth.

00:03:20.100 --> 00:03:23.310
And he really kickstarted
a large research program

00:03:23.310 --> 00:03:27.810
in this vision where
you would be able to--

00:03:27.810 --> 00:03:30.510
a simple chemical reaction
between hydrogen and oxygen

00:03:30.510 --> 00:03:31.800
generates energy.

00:03:31.800 --> 00:03:32.850
What's that called?

00:03:36.280 --> 00:03:38.510
There's a device that does that.

00:03:38.510 --> 00:03:39.603
That's a fuel cell.

00:03:39.603 --> 00:03:41.270
We're not going to
talk about that part.

00:03:41.270 --> 00:03:43.485
We're not talking about what
you do with the hydrogen

00:03:43.485 --> 00:03:45.110
because there's all
kinds of challenges

00:03:45.110 --> 00:03:46.650
there too, by the way.

00:03:46.650 --> 00:03:47.570
OK.

00:03:47.570 --> 00:03:49.340
So there's really
great research going

00:03:49.340 --> 00:03:52.820
on in fuel cells, which are
what you put the hydrogen into

00:03:52.820 --> 00:03:54.255
to make electricity.

00:03:57.950 --> 00:03:59.660
There is a new
national commitment.

00:03:59.660 --> 00:04:01.310
And there's going to be--

00:04:01.310 --> 00:04:03.170
first car driven by
a child born today

00:04:03.170 --> 00:04:06.110
could be powered by
hydrogen and pollution free.

00:04:06.110 --> 00:04:06.950
Yes.

00:04:06.950 --> 00:04:09.730
For $10 million per car.

00:04:09.730 --> 00:04:11.590
OK.

00:04:11.590 --> 00:04:14.320
I mean, I think a lot of
people were excited about this.

00:04:14.320 --> 00:04:18.100
But this is a very
large investment

00:04:18.100 --> 00:04:22.420
for government research,
which is very little money.

00:04:22.420 --> 00:04:25.480
And in a technology
that clearly has

00:04:25.480 --> 00:04:28.330
at least 50 years
of research that's

00:04:28.330 --> 00:04:31.840
needed before you're
going to see a trial.

00:04:31.840 --> 00:04:36.520
So maybe this should have said
a child's future grandchild

00:04:36.520 --> 00:04:37.720
born today.

00:04:37.720 --> 00:04:39.140
And that would be cool.

00:04:39.140 --> 00:04:40.390
OK.

00:04:40.390 --> 00:04:43.930
And yet, there are some
really great programs going on

00:04:43.930 --> 00:04:47.445
to test the hydrogen economy.

00:04:47.445 --> 00:04:48.820
And those are the
kinds of things

00:04:48.820 --> 00:04:52.113
we need to do now to lay
the groundwork for all

00:04:52.113 --> 00:04:53.780
the challenges that
have to be overcome.

00:04:53.780 --> 00:04:56.287
Again, I'm just going
to talk about one

00:04:56.287 --> 00:04:57.370
of them, which is storage.

00:04:57.370 --> 00:05:00.100
But so I don't--

00:05:00.100 --> 00:05:03.190
now, then Obama came in
and he slashed the budget.

00:05:03.190 --> 00:05:05.980
Actually, he tried to kill it--

00:05:05.980 --> 00:05:09.460
the hydrogen research in this
country to 0, which I thought

00:05:09.460 --> 00:05:13.720
was interesting because
in that administration

00:05:13.720 --> 00:05:17.492
the sense was well,
it's a great technology.

00:05:17.492 --> 00:05:18.700
But it's a very long way off.

00:05:18.700 --> 00:05:20.290
Let's try to work on--

00:05:20.290 --> 00:05:23.770
reshuffle our investment a
little into other things.

00:05:23.770 --> 00:05:26.940
Things that might
give a shorter return

00:05:26.940 --> 00:05:31.570
in terms of technologies that
are needed in clean energy

00:05:31.570 --> 00:05:33.240
more rapidly.

00:05:33.240 --> 00:05:34.660
OK.

00:05:34.660 --> 00:05:35.680
I've already shown this.

00:05:35.680 --> 00:05:39.610
I love this history of hydrogen.
When you have a moment, just

00:05:39.610 --> 00:05:41.710
read some Jules
Verne where he said--

00:05:41.710 --> 00:05:43.450
I think I already
read this quote.

00:05:43.450 --> 00:05:46.390
But he said, "I believe that one
day hydrogen and oxygen, which

00:05:46.390 --> 00:05:49.060
together form water will
be used either alone

00:05:49.060 --> 00:05:52.300
or together as an inexhaustible
source of heat and light."

00:05:52.300 --> 00:05:55.840
I think that's really cool
that was in the 1800s.

00:05:55.840 --> 00:05:58.420
And then there are
some things that

00:05:58.420 --> 00:06:05.560
happened along the way like that
blimp thing that I showed you.

00:06:05.560 --> 00:06:09.310
But see, now that has caused
a lot of misunderstanding

00:06:09.310 --> 00:06:14.680
about hydrogen in that
it's, yes, it can combust.

00:06:14.680 --> 00:06:16.730
But how dangerous is it?

00:06:16.730 --> 00:06:20.470
So I'll show you
a slide on that.

00:06:20.470 --> 00:06:20.970
Right.

00:06:20.970 --> 00:06:25.920
So the problem in the storage is
that the low volumetric density

00:06:25.920 --> 00:06:28.110
of anything that's
a gas requires

00:06:28.110 --> 00:06:29.610
something that can densify it.

00:06:29.610 --> 00:06:32.130
So you got to
compress it basically.

00:06:32.130 --> 00:06:34.770
Here's your metric gasoline.

00:06:34.770 --> 00:06:39.240
Remember, gasoline is this
beautiful high energy density

00:06:39.240 --> 00:06:41.460
way of storing energy.

00:06:41.460 --> 00:06:45.510
32 megajoules per liter
compared with liquid hydrogen--

00:06:45.510 --> 00:06:47.250
if you can liquefy it, it's 8.

00:06:47.250 --> 00:06:49.350
And gas under very
high pressure--

00:06:49.350 --> 00:06:53.070
5,000 PSI is only 3.

00:06:53.070 --> 00:06:56.670
So even if I squeeze
this hydrogen gas a ton,

00:06:56.670 --> 00:07:00.450
it's still only a tenth of the
energy density of gasoline.

00:07:00.450 --> 00:07:00.950
OK.

00:07:00.950 --> 00:07:05.180
So that's why storing enough
hydrogen on board is hard.

00:07:05.180 --> 00:07:09.950
And it adds a lot of
weight and volume.

00:07:09.950 --> 00:07:13.220
And this would be how much--
this is a little less.

00:07:13.220 --> 00:07:15.290
This is about 3,000 PSI--

00:07:15.290 --> 00:07:18.900
200 bar-- so that would
be a gas tank of hydrogen,

00:07:18.900 --> 00:07:22.910
which is currently how some
car manufacturers are making

00:07:22.910 --> 00:07:24.320
hydrogen powered cars--

00:07:24.320 --> 00:07:28.820
again, $10, $20
million per vehicle--

00:07:28.820 --> 00:07:30.600
that store hydrogen this way.

00:07:30.600 --> 00:07:32.060
OK.

00:07:32.060 --> 00:07:34.538
If you could liquefy it, you
can get down to smaller tanks.

00:07:34.538 --> 00:07:36.830
What I want to tell you about
is something that I think

00:07:36.830 --> 00:07:41.340
is really exciting here, which
is a chemical storage approach.

00:07:41.340 --> 00:07:44.250
OK.

00:07:44.250 --> 00:07:47.470
Now, right.

00:07:47.470 --> 00:07:48.292
OK.

00:07:48.292 --> 00:07:50.500
Of course, you can imagine
that when you store things

00:07:50.500 --> 00:07:54.970
at this high pressure or at low
temperatures and high pressures

00:07:54.970 --> 00:07:58.900
you have very challenging
engineering and packaging

00:07:58.900 --> 00:07:59.710
issues.

00:07:59.710 --> 00:08:02.350
And that's one of
the biggest concerns.

00:08:02.350 --> 00:08:05.315
And because there's also
a lot of misunderstanding

00:08:05.315 --> 00:08:06.440
of the safety of hydrogen--

00:08:06.440 --> 00:08:09.590
I'm not saying it's
completely safe.

00:08:09.590 --> 00:08:12.820
But people actually are
looking at the safety

00:08:12.820 --> 00:08:15.540
of having something
under that much pressure.

00:08:15.540 --> 00:08:17.010
OK.

00:08:17.010 --> 00:08:19.470
And so actually, when you
have a hydrogen powered car,

00:08:19.470 --> 00:08:24.280
you tend to do a drop test,
which isn't really true.

00:08:24.280 --> 00:08:26.500
They just are doing drop
tests on the containers

00:08:26.500 --> 00:08:28.250
that they're developing.

00:08:28.250 --> 00:08:28.750
And

00:08:28.750 --> 00:08:31.000
They drop it so that
it's going to impact

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:34.030
the ground at 52 miles an hour.

00:08:34.030 --> 00:08:39.039
And I guarantee you that
one exploding drop test,

00:08:39.039 --> 00:08:45.520
and the market is going to have
some serious issues whatever

00:08:45.520 --> 00:08:47.620
the cause of it is.

00:08:47.620 --> 00:08:50.800
But this is a real
concern is the safety--

00:08:50.800 --> 00:08:52.480
forget about whether
it's hydrogen.

00:08:52.480 --> 00:08:55.270
But if you store anything
under that high pressure,

00:08:55.270 --> 00:08:57.880
there are serious safety
concerns and real packaging

00:08:57.880 --> 00:08:58.620
challenges.

00:08:58.620 --> 00:09:01.280
OK.

00:09:01.280 --> 00:09:03.370
Remember, it's not just
how the package operates

00:09:03.370 --> 00:09:04.960
when you buy it,
it's how it operates

00:09:04.960 --> 00:09:08.940
after 10 years of
corrosion and operation.

00:09:08.940 --> 00:09:09.480
OK.

00:09:09.480 --> 00:09:13.390
So I think chemical storage is
a really interesting way to go.

00:09:13.390 --> 00:09:17.380
It does not involve
high pressures.

00:09:17.380 --> 00:09:17.880
OK.

00:09:17.880 --> 00:09:21.780
Basically, in chemical
storage, what you have is

00:09:21.780 --> 00:09:23.460
you have essentially a sponge.

00:09:23.460 --> 00:09:27.870
You have a material
that soaks hydrogen up.

00:09:27.870 --> 00:09:29.730
So it literally just
absorbs hydrogen

00:09:29.730 --> 00:09:33.130
and it changes into a hydride.

00:09:33.130 --> 00:09:35.710
And then you pull
the hydrogen back out

00:09:35.710 --> 00:09:37.280
and it's just a sponge.

00:09:37.280 --> 00:09:39.520
OK.

00:09:39.520 --> 00:09:41.840
Now the problem is that--

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:43.815
and there are lots
of references.

00:09:43.815 --> 00:09:45.940
And there's lots of great
places to read about some

00:09:45.940 --> 00:09:46.523
of this stuff.

00:09:46.523 --> 00:09:49.070
And I've put them here--
put some of them here.

00:09:49.070 --> 00:09:51.430
This is a really nice review.

00:09:51.430 --> 00:09:54.470
And the problem is if you
look at the periodic table,

00:09:54.470 --> 00:09:57.605
you see a lot of times we're
excited about materials design.

00:09:57.605 --> 00:09:59.230
And we look at the
whole periodic table

00:09:59.230 --> 00:10:01.190
and say, what
should we do today?

00:10:01.190 --> 00:10:01.840
Right?

00:10:01.840 --> 00:10:03.100
Don't you all feel that way?

00:10:03.100 --> 00:10:04.005
That's how I feel.

00:10:04.005 --> 00:10:06.130
Every morning-- like what
am I going to make today?

00:10:06.130 --> 00:10:07.920
Polonium!

00:10:07.920 --> 00:10:10.400
No.

00:10:10.400 --> 00:10:12.230
Ciborium.

00:10:12.230 --> 00:10:14.360
Where's ciborium?

00:10:14.360 --> 00:10:15.860
There it is.

00:10:15.860 --> 00:10:16.850
OK.

00:10:16.850 --> 00:10:17.990
That's a neat material.

00:10:17.990 --> 00:10:20.660
Ciborium carbide is
higher than diamond.

00:10:20.660 --> 00:10:22.530
It's harder than diamond.

00:10:22.530 --> 00:10:23.030
Right?

00:10:23.030 --> 00:10:24.980
Now it's a problem
that see ciborium only

00:10:24.980 --> 00:10:28.220
exists for 10 to the minus--

00:10:28.220 --> 00:10:30.650
I don't know-- 5
seconds or something.

00:10:30.650 --> 00:10:32.600
But still, for that
short of a time

00:10:32.600 --> 00:10:34.820
you can make really
hard materials with it.

00:10:34.820 --> 00:10:36.200
But see-- now-- OK--

00:10:36.200 --> 00:10:37.670
it's a little tangent.

00:10:37.670 --> 00:10:42.480
For hydrogen storage, you got a
big problem, which is density.

00:10:42.480 --> 00:10:42.980
Right?

00:10:42.980 --> 00:10:44.870
So if you're going
to use a sponge

00:10:44.870 --> 00:10:48.890
to soak hydrogen up and then
release it when you need it

00:10:48.890 --> 00:10:51.440
and then soak it back
up, the sponge can't

00:10:51.440 --> 00:10:56.070
weigh 1,000 times more than
the hydrogen. That's a problem.

00:10:56.070 --> 00:10:56.570
Right?

00:10:56.570 --> 00:10:59.390
Because then you're just going
to add thousands of pounds

00:10:59.390 --> 00:11:01.310
of weight to your car.

00:11:01.310 --> 00:11:03.720
So that really limits
what you can use.

00:11:03.720 --> 00:11:06.350
And so only the light
elements are really

00:11:06.350 --> 00:11:07.520
going to be useful here.

00:11:07.520 --> 00:11:08.900
And then you have a short list.

00:11:08.900 --> 00:11:10.370
And then you say,
I don't want them

00:11:10.370 --> 00:11:12.180
to be really that poisonous.

00:11:12.180 --> 00:11:14.700
It might not be a good thing
in the back of your car.

00:11:14.700 --> 00:11:16.040
Right?

00:11:16.040 --> 00:11:18.620
And so then the list--
you can essentially

00:11:18.620 --> 00:11:21.800
argue that the list is about
eight elements that you

00:11:21.800 --> 00:11:22.850
might store.

00:11:22.850 --> 00:11:25.100
And that's just not a
lot of room to play.

00:11:25.100 --> 00:11:27.510
That's why this is challenging.

00:11:27.510 --> 00:11:29.610
As I'm going to show
you, there actually

00:11:29.610 --> 00:11:31.740
is more room than you think.

00:11:31.740 --> 00:11:34.390
More and more room
as research goes on.

00:11:34.390 --> 00:11:35.610
OK.

00:11:35.610 --> 00:11:38.250
And so there are a lot
of materials that do fall

00:11:38.250 --> 00:11:40.510
into-- when you combine these
eight elements together,

00:11:40.510 --> 00:11:42.780
you can make many
different materials.

00:11:42.780 --> 00:11:47.460
And they do fall into
a range of categories--

00:11:47.460 --> 00:11:49.800
kinds of structures,
