00:19:18.487 --> 00:19:20.570
But you can see that there's
still some variation.

00:19:20.570 --> 00:19:26.210
If I go to classical potentials,
it's very, very hard to know,

00:19:26.210 --> 00:19:28.910
when I engineer something
into a new domain like this,

00:19:28.910 --> 00:19:31.250
if it's right.

00:19:31.250 --> 00:19:33.500
So this is really
a problem that's

00:19:33.500 --> 00:19:38.895
best suited for accurate
quantum mechanical methods,

00:19:38.895 --> 00:19:41.270
because you're going to make
a classical potential that's

00:19:41.270 --> 00:19:42.860
fit here, basically.

00:19:42.860 --> 00:19:45.710
But all of the interesting
stuff happens as you go down

00:19:45.710 --> 00:19:47.300
to smaller sizes.

00:19:47.300 --> 00:19:49.140
So it goes down
into this window.

00:19:49.140 --> 00:19:52.483
So notice that I might
want it in this range.

00:19:52.483 --> 00:19:53.900
I might want the
desorbtion energy

00:19:53.900 --> 00:19:57.170
to be in this range, which means
I have a very narrow window

00:19:57.170 --> 00:20:00.090
of size that I can pick.

00:20:00.090 --> 00:20:02.870
I better get that
right, that size right,

00:20:02.870 --> 00:20:05.510
if I'm going to try to make
predictions of new materials.

00:20:05.510 --> 00:20:08.330
And that's where-- again, and
