00:44:39.210 --> 00:44:40.890
So now, we get to
Bloch's Theorem,

00:44:40.890 --> 00:44:47.340
which is what gets us to
this dependence, this wiggle,

00:44:47.340 --> 00:44:48.570
this wiggle.

00:44:48.570 --> 00:44:51.060
So we're setting it up.

00:44:51.060 --> 00:44:52.650
We have reciprocal space.

00:44:52.650 --> 00:44:57.000
We defined this first
zone in reciprocal space.

00:44:57.000 --> 00:44:59.700
We said that, if you go through
the zone, things change.

00:44:59.700 --> 00:45:01.650
Bloch's Theorem is the reason.

00:45:01.650 --> 00:45:03.540
It's the reason
why things change

00:45:03.540 --> 00:45:04.950
as you tour through this zone.

00:45:07.558 --> 00:45:09.850
There are different ways to
talk about Bloch's Theorem.

00:45:09.850 --> 00:45:11.650
Here's a fairly simple
way to look at it.

00:45:14.340 --> 00:45:19.620
So if you write the reciprocal
lattice vector like this,

00:45:19.620 --> 00:45:22.320
2 pi-- and the
2's are just there

00:45:22.320 --> 00:45:24.630
to make math a
little easier, so you

00:45:24.630 --> 00:45:27.070
can write it however you want.

00:45:27.070 --> 00:45:28.170
This is that integer.

00:45:28.170 --> 00:45:30.690
There's the reciprocal
lattice vector.

00:45:30.690 --> 00:45:34.950
If you write it like that, then,
if you take this exponential--

00:45:34.950 --> 00:45:36.420
[SNEEZE]

00:45:36.420 --> 00:45:42.020
--gesundheit-- which I've
already alluded to before,

00:45:42.020 --> 00:45:45.260
and you do that,
actually, explicitly out.

00:45:45.260 --> 00:45:48.230
So R is a vector in real space.

00:45:50.980 --> 00:45:52.540
R is a vector in real space.

00:45:52.540 --> 00:45:57.880
Now, if I dot R with G, which
is a reciprocal lattice vector,

00:45:57.880 --> 00:46:01.520
then I get the reciprocal
lattice vector dot that.

00:46:01.520 --> 00:46:04.660
And that's just alpha, beta,
gamma, or just the coefficients

00:46:04.660 --> 00:46:06.370
of the real space
lattice vector,

00:46:06.370 --> 00:46:08.538
because R will be
somewhere in real space.

00:46:08.538 --> 00:46:11.080
And so I can represent it, in
terms of the real space lattice

00:46:11.080 --> 00:46:14.710
vectors time some coefficients.

00:46:14.710 --> 00:46:17.770
And what you can see when you
do this, it's very simple math.

00:46:17.770 --> 00:46:19.870
What you can see is
that, as you vary where

00:46:19.870 --> 00:46:23.440
you are in real space,
then, well, these things

00:46:23.440 --> 00:46:24.340
are going to change.

00:46:24.340 --> 00:46:27.040
Alpha, beta, and gamma would
change between, say, 0 and 1.

00:46:30.030 --> 00:46:33.350
And the function e to
the iG.r changes as well.

00:46:36.530 --> 00:46:40.100
But you can see from
this little derivation

00:46:40.100 --> 00:46:44.720
that, since these are integers,
this function is always going

00:46:44.720 --> 00:46:45.990
to vary with the periodicity.

00:46:45.990 --> 00:46:47.000
So this is what I said.

00:46:47.000 --> 00:46:48.530
Here's the math behind it.

00:46:48.530 --> 00:46:50.090
I said this before.

00:46:50.090 --> 00:46:54.020
So you now have a
function, e to the iG.R

00:46:54.020 --> 00:46:56.343
And that's the reason why.

00:46:56.343 --> 00:46:58.260
If you just spend a few
minutes staring at it,

00:46:58.260 --> 00:47:00.980
you'll see why this is true.

00:47:00.980 --> 00:47:03.745
You have a way of making
a function automatically

00:47:03.745 --> 00:47:04.245
periodic.

00:47:07.070 --> 00:47:11.030
Now, why do I care?

00:47:11.030 --> 00:47:14.410
Well, because if I
have this periodicity,

00:47:14.410 --> 00:47:17.020
if I have this ordering--

00:47:17.020 --> 00:47:18.700
here, it's drawn is
an approximation.

00:47:18.700 --> 00:47:20.840
Here, it's drawn as
maybe more realistic,

00:47:20.840 --> 00:47:22.150
what my potentials look like.

00:47:27.640 --> 00:47:32.740
Then the values of some
function, like the density,

00:47:32.740 --> 00:47:36.020
should be what at
each lattice site?

00:47:36.020 --> 00:47:39.320
Well, I have it there in blue.

00:47:39.320 --> 00:47:41.283
AUDIENCE: They'd be
identical [INAUDIBLE]

00:47:41.283 --> 00:47:42.450
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Thank you.

00:47:42.450 --> 00:47:45.240
Thank you very much.

00:47:45.240 --> 00:47:50.910
Now, that seems obvious.

00:47:50.910 --> 00:47:52.980
I mean, I've got,
basically, an array

00:47:52.980 --> 00:47:56.460
that goes on forever that's
the same every lattice vector.

00:47:56.460 --> 00:47:58.030
It's just the same thing.

00:47:58.030 --> 00:48:00.390
This is a pure, perfect crystal.

00:48:00.390 --> 00:48:03.480
There are no defects.

00:48:03.480 --> 00:48:07.200
It's completely unrealistic,
because, as you all know,

00:48:07.200 --> 00:48:08.820
there are defects in reality.

00:48:08.820 --> 00:48:11.382
But we can put those into
the simulation as well.

00:48:11.382 --> 00:48:13.215
But for this derivation,
there's no defects.

00:48:13.215 --> 00:48:15.640
So you have infinite crystal.

00:48:15.640 --> 00:48:18.780
And what that means is that,
everywhere, the properties

00:48:18.780 --> 00:48:19.600
should be the same.

00:48:19.600 --> 00:48:22.300
If I sit on this atom or this
atom or in between these two

00:48:22.300 --> 00:48:24.175
and then in between
those two, the properties

00:48:24.175 --> 00:48:27.000
should be the same, if I
go by a lattice vector.

00:48:27.000 --> 00:48:28.230
Here's the kicker, though.

00:48:28.230 --> 00:48:30.720
The wave function
is not the same.

00:48:33.770 --> 00:48:35.150
And that's really the key.

00:48:35.150 --> 00:48:38.030
The wave function
is not the same.

00:48:38.030 --> 00:48:39.800
It's almost the
same, but it's not.

00:48:42.320 --> 00:48:43.430
It's periodic.

00:48:43.430 --> 00:48:45.320
The wave function
is periodic but only

00:48:45.320 --> 00:48:49.160
when it's multiplied
by a phase factor.

00:48:49.160 --> 00:48:50.710
And that is Bloch's Theorem.

00:48:50.710 --> 00:48:52.460
And there are three
or four different ways

00:48:52.460 --> 00:48:53.450
that it can be derived.

00:48:53.450 --> 00:48:55.670
I will post them onto
the Stellar website.

00:48:55.670 --> 00:48:59.150
They're not something you need
to know for quiz or homework.

00:48:59.150 --> 00:49:00.650
But that is Bloch's Theorem.

00:49:00.650 --> 00:49:04.280
It's that the wave function
in a infinitely repeating

00:49:04.280 --> 00:49:12.800
periodic crystal is going
to equal some function that

00:49:12.800 --> 00:49:16.450
is periodic, some
function that's

00:49:16.450 --> 00:49:19.810
periodic that has the
periodicity of the lattice,

00:49:19.810 --> 00:49:23.620
some function, u,
times the phase.

00:49:23.620 --> 00:49:25.570
And that, this is
that function u.

00:49:25.570 --> 00:49:27.430
You see, it's periodic.

00:49:27.430 --> 00:49:32.900
It equals it, if you go plus
big R, plus one lattice vector.

00:49:32.900 --> 00:49:34.817
So if you move over by a whole--

00:49:34.817 --> 00:49:36.400
when I see lattice
vector, by the way,

00:49:36.400 --> 00:49:37.780
let's bring it to reality.

00:49:37.780 --> 00:49:41.860
I just mean if
silicon were cubic,

00:49:41.860 --> 00:49:44.790
I'd just be going from one
silicon atom to another.

00:49:44.790 --> 00:49:45.790
That's a lattice vector.

00:49:50.230 --> 00:49:54.570
And simple cubic, I'm thinking.

00:49:54.570 --> 00:49:57.600
And so you have a
function that also

00:49:57.600 --> 00:50:00.980
is the same in that
lattice distance,

00:50:00.980 --> 00:50:04.040
as you go from, say, one atom
to another in the simplest case.

00:50:04.040 --> 00:50:06.140
But the wave function
is that times the phase.

00:50:06.140 --> 00:50:07.940
And that's really
important, because that

00:50:07.940 --> 00:50:10.620
brings in a new variable.

00:50:10.620 --> 00:50:12.980
In fact, this is a
new quantum number.

00:50:12.980 --> 00:50:14.480
That brings in a
new quantum number.

00:50:18.250 --> 00:50:22.840
This is a quantum number, k,
that lives in inverse space.

00:50:27.950 --> 00:50:38.500
So Bloch's Theorem says that,
if I go from one point in space

00:50:38.500 --> 00:50:42.220
to another point that's
translated by just a lattice

00:50:42.220 --> 00:50:48.430
factor, then I equal my original
wave function time this phase.

00:50:48.430 --> 00:50:49.750
And you can show--

00:50:49.750 --> 00:50:51.280
I mean, this is
actually trivial,

00:50:51.280 --> 00:50:53.360
because this is
a complex number.

00:50:53.360 --> 00:50:55.570
So when you square
it, you can show

00:50:55.570 --> 00:50:58.390
that the squares are the same,
which is really important.

00:50:58.390 --> 00:51:02.290
The charge density in
the lattice is periodic.

00:51:02.290 --> 00:51:04.930
Does everybody see that?

00:51:04.930 --> 00:51:07.150
The charge density in a
crystal should be periodic.

00:51:07.150 --> 00:51:09.880
Between any two
silicon atoms, the bond

00:51:09.880 --> 00:51:14.510
is the same for as long as
you can see, 10 to 23rd bonds.

00:51:14.510 --> 00:51:16.580
It's a whole lot of sameness.

00:51:16.580 --> 00:51:18.860
And you can see that the
equations show that it is.

00:51:18.860 --> 00:51:23.960
But the wave function
can vary by this phase.

00:51:23.960 --> 00:51:29.630
You can also show that if
psi k, this thing that I'm

00:51:29.630 --> 00:51:33.530
going to talk about more, is
a solution to the Schrodinger

00:51:33.530 --> 00:51:37.913
equation, then psi k
plus any reciprocal--

00:51:37.913 --> 00:51:39.080
this is a reciprocal number.

00:51:39.080 --> 00:51:40.370
Remember, this is a number.

00:51:40.370 --> 00:51:44.570
k is a vector in
reciprocal space.

00:51:44.570 --> 00:51:46.610
That's the Bloch's Theorem.

00:51:46.610 --> 00:51:50.450
That's a reciprocal vector
that lives in reciprocal space

00:51:50.450 --> 00:51:54.860
dotted with the lattice vector.

00:51:54.860 --> 00:51:58.610
And if I add the reciprocal
lattice vector to it,

00:51:58.610 --> 00:52:00.630
then that also
must be a solution.

00:52:00.630 --> 00:52:03.470
So that's also another
consequence of Bloch's Theorem.

00:52:03.470 --> 00:52:06.215
So here's the--

00:52:06.215 --> 00:52:08.480
I know some of you
might not quite

00:52:08.480 --> 00:52:10.580
be feeling your
