00:58:37.470 --> 00:58:44.100
And you can get a feel for--

00:58:44.100 --> 00:58:50.970
as you vary k, so then things
happen, like the momentum

00:58:50.970 --> 00:58:53.970
can change.

00:58:53.970 --> 00:59:00.140
And that means the
velocity can change.

00:59:00.140 --> 00:59:02.330
And if the velocity can change--

00:59:02.330 --> 00:59:06.290
well, actually, the
mass can change as well.

00:59:06.290 --> 00:59:08.390
And if those things can change--

00:59:08.390 --> 00:59:09.890
of course, it's not
really changing.

00:59:09.890 --> 00:59:12.020
The mass of the electron
isn't really changing.

00:59:12.020 --> 00:59:16.910
But the effective mass, the mass
that it feels in the crystal,

00:59:16.910 --> 00:59:18.460
is changing.

00:59:18.460 --> 00:59:19.940
And, boy, is that important.

00:59:19.940 --> 00:59:24.910
And we'll talk about that,
because, from the way that--

00:59:24.910 --> 00:59:27.670
here's my levels in
an atom or molecule.

00:59:27.670 --> 00:59:30.340
And now, remember, I
said that they do this.

00:59:30.340 --> 00:59:35.420
From the way they do this, how
heavy an electron feels itself

00:59:35.420 --> 00:59:38.930
to be in the crystal varies.

00:59:38.930 --> 00:59:44.830
It has an effective mass that's
dependent on the wiggles here.

00:59:44.830 --> 00:59:47.610
And because of that,
that's directly related

00:59:47.610 --> 00:59:51.090
to how fast an electron can
cruise through the crystal.

00:59:51.090 --> 00:59:53.620
It's directly related
to the mobility.

00:59:53.620 --> 00:59:55.530
So the transport
properties are deeply

00:59:55.530 --> 00:59:58.110
dependent on this wiggling.

01:00:01.050 --> 01:00:03.000
So Bloch's Theorem
is a formal theorem

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:06.060
that tells you that you have
to write wave functions in such

01:00:06.060 --> 01:00:10.050
a way that you have a dependence
on the inverse lattice.

01:00:10.050 --> 01:00:16.680
And then how that dependence
enters into a system

01:00:16.680 --> 01:00:19.050
or a material is very complex.

01:00:19.050 --> 01:00:21.300
And it depends on solving
the Schrodinger equation

01:00:21.300 --> 01:00:22.008
for the material.

01:00:26.180 --> 01:00:30.020
But you see, you can think
about it like this, if you want.

01:00:30.020 --> 01:00:31.730
Here's my inverse space.

01:00:31.730 --> 01:00:36.030
And I'm going to change where
I am in reciprocal space.

01:00:36.030 --> 01:00:38.180
Remember, again, I only
have reciprocal space

01:00:38.180 --> 01:00:39.870
because I have a crystal.

01:00:39.870 --> 01:00:41.660
I have a lattice.

01:00:41.660 --> 01:00:43.160
So I have an inverse space.

01:00:43.160 --> 01:00:45.380
And if I change where
I am in inverse space,

01:00:45.380 --> 01:00:48.620
these would be my
new energy levels.

01:00:48.620 --> 01:00:50.880
You get a new set
of energy levels,

01:00:50.880 --> 01:00:55.160
those e's that I just showed
you, for every point in space,

01:00:55.160 --> 01:00:58.050
in k-space, every
point in k-space.

01:00:58.050 --> 01:01:00.870
So now, this is just blown up.

01:01:00.870 --> 01:01:05.440
It used to be the good
old days, last Thursday.

01:01:05.440 --> 01:01:07.120
We just had these levels.

01:01:07.120 --> 01:01:10.330
We just got through talking
about how you get these from--

01:01:10.330 --> 01:01:12.490
you can build up two
atoms, three atoms.

01:01:12.490 --> 01:01:13.780
And you get these levels.

01:01:13.780 --> 01:01:15.140
And they didn't go anywhere.

01:01:15.140 --> 01:01:17.890
And now, they've blown up,
because anywhere you go

01:01:17.890 --> 01:01:21.270
in this reciprocal
space, they can change.

01:01:21.270 --> 01:01:23.030
They can change.

01:01:23.030 --> 01:01:26.170
So now, you need to
compute those same levels

01:01:26.170 --> 01:01:30.310
in the computer for
different points in k-space.

01:01:30.310 --> 01:01:33.670
And that's what a computer does
when it solves for a solid.

01:01:33.670 --> 01:01:34.720
That's what it does.

01:01:34.720 --> 01:01:37.390
That's basically the
difference, is you now

01:01:37.390 --> 01:01:41.680
have an extra degree of
freedom that you didn't have

01:01:41.680 --> 01:01:46.330
in your atoms and molecules
or an extra quantum number

01:01:46.330 --> 01:01:49.830
that you need to explore, k.

01:01:49.830 --> 01:01:51.390
So what are my levels at 0?

01:01:51.390 --> 01:01:52.650
Well, there are these.

01:01:52.650 --> 01:01:53.440
I don't know.

01:01:53.440 --> 01:01:54.480
Well, they're not here.

01:01:54.480 --> 01:01:55.320
What are my levels here?

01:01:55.320 --> 01:01:56.070
They look like this.

01:01:56.070 --> 01:01:57.070
Here, they look at this.

01:01:57.070 --> 01:01:58.740
And that's how the
computer does it.

01:01:58.740 --> 01:02:00.240
It computes the same thing.

01:02:00.240 --> 01:02:02.970
It computes the energy
levels, fills them up.

01:02:02.970 --> 01:02:05.850
But at each point in k-space,
they can be different.

01:02:05.850 --> 01:02:08.850
And this is exactly
that difference.

01:02:08.850 --> 01:02:10.650
You change where
you are in k-space.

01:02:10.650 --> 01:02:11.460
And look at that.

01:02:11.460 --> 01:02:13.680
This level starts going down.

01:02:13.680 --> 01:02:15.650
This level goes up.

01:02:15.650 --> 01:02:18.040
I don't know what's
going on here.

01:02:18.040 --> 01:02:19.270
Maybe that's this one.

01:02:19.270 --> 01:02:20.230
That one's going up.

01:02:20.230 --> 01:02:24.360
All kinds of things can
happen as you cruise around

01:02:24.360 --> 01:02:27.890
phase space, in k-space.

01:02:27.890 --> 01:02:30.420
Those energy levels will change.

01:02:30.420 --> 01:02:32.947
And that is what leads
to a band structure.

01:02:32.947 --> 01:02:34.280
That's what a band structure is.

01:02:41.000 --> 01:02:44.960
It's just a continuous
change of energy levels

01:02:44.960 --> 01:02:46.220
as a function of k-space.

01:02:49.650 --> 01:02:54.690
And each of these bands is
still just an energy level.

01:02:54.690 --> 01:02:57.150
So how many
electrons go into it?

01:02:57.150 --> 01:02:59.210
Still just an energy
level, it's just

01:02:59.210 --> 01:03:02.600
a weird one that wiggles
depending on where you

01:03:02.600 --> 01:03:04.310
are in the reciprocal lattice.

01:03:04.310 --> 01:03:06.590
But how many electrons
do I put into this band

01:03:06.590 --> 01:03:09.310
as I fill them up?

01:03:09.310 --> 01:03:13.510
Two, I still just put
two electrons in here.

01:03:13.510 --> 01:03:15.160
And then I put two
electrons in here.

01:03:15.160 --> 01:03:16.577
And then I put two
electrons here.

01:03:16.577 --> 01:03:17.500
Oh, but look at that.

01:03:17.500 --> 01:03:19.420
It was actually two bands.

01:03:19.420 --> 01:03:21.350
That's tricky.

01:03:21.350 --> 01:03:23.890
So you get these really
interesting behaviors,

01:03:23.890 --> 01:03:26.320
where bands can merge
and become degenerate.

01:03:26.320 --> 01:03:30.880
Ah, but that's not really
that different, is it,

01:03:30.880 --> 01:03:33.040
then the idea that
you could have

01:03:33.040 --> 01:03:39.700
states like this, where I had--
this is just the atom, 1S 2S,

01:03:39.700 --> 01:03:41.200
2P.

01:03:41.200 --> 01:03:46.360
I had three energy bands
that had the same energy.

01:03:46.360 --> 01:03:47.980
That's called degeneracy.

01:03:47.980 --> 01:03:50.080
Here it is in the hydrogen atom.

01:03:50.080 --> 01:03:52.360
There it is in a
very complex crystal.

01:03:52.360 --> 01:03:55.490
Well, it's actually
a simple crystal.

01:03:55.490 --> 01:03:57.470
So you have
degeneracies, where--

01:03:57.470 --> 01:04:01.190
these would be like two levels
that are the same energy.

01:04:01.190 --> 01:04:03.860
But now, I'm cruising
around in k-space.

01:04:03.860 --> 01:04:07.100
And I get to a part of
k-space where they no longer

01:04:07.100 --> 01:04:07.680
are the same.

01:04:07.680 --> 01:04:08.720
They actually split.

01:04:08.720 --> 01:04:09.650
This one goes down.

01:04:09.650 --> 01:04:13.100
And these two go up, let's say.

01:04:13.100 --> 01:04:16.260
And so their degeneracy splits.

01:04:16.260 --> 01:04:19.740
And you see that all the
time in band structures.

01:04:19.740 --> 01:04:21.930
But there are a certain
number of total levels here.

01:04:21.930 --> 01:04:23.347
And you fill them
up, just like we

01:04:23.347 --> 01:04:26.190
did for an atom or a molecule.

01:04:26.190 --> 01:04:30.570
Now, somebody tell me what--
so that's a band structure.

